taskpane$semi$ model selection details:
Choose one of the three options to recover your password:

Wizard - walks you step-by-step through setting up your search for a password. It is best for situations where you know something about the password, but are new to password recovery.

Predefined Settings - best if you do not know anything about the password. Default attacks will be launched.

Customized Settings - best if you know something about the password and are an experienced IT person. You can choose which attacks you want to use, modify attack settings, and combine attacks.
taskpane$semi$ node description for Memo:
If there is a memory image of a computer, acquired while this file was open, the Encryption Keys Extraction Attack instantly extracts the encryption keys from the memory image and decrypts the file, regardless of the password length.

Please specify the memory image or the system hibernation file (hiberfil.sys) for this attack.
taskpane$semi$ node description for Sure: SureZip Attack decrypts most WinZip archives in less than an hour regardless of their passwords. At least five simultaneously encrypted files are required in order to process the archive. Archives created with WinZip are supported.
taskpane$semi$ node description for Zip:
If there is at least one file from a password protected Zip archive available unencrypted, the Zip Plaintext Attack instantly decrypts the whole archive for you, regardless of the password length.

Please compress the known file with the same version of Zip and then apply it to the Zip Plaintext Attack as a Plaintext archive.
taskpane$semi$ node description for appe:
Append Attacks group runs attacks to check the shortest passwords first, then runs the same attacks to check increasingly longer passwords.

When Append Attacks group is not enabled, Passware Kit checks all the passwords of each attack before running the next attack.
taskpane$semi$ node description for bf: Brute-force Attack checks all combinations of characters according to the current attack settings. This is the slowest, but most thorough, method.
taskpane$semi$ node description for cach: Previous Passwords Attack checks passwords that were previously recovered by other attacks for other files. It automatically saves all passwords found.
taskpane$semi$ node description for cons:
Known Password/Part Attack checks a certain password entered in the "Value" field. There is no need to open a file in order to check whether a certain password is correct.

This attack can be combined with other attacks using the Join Attacks option. For example, if you know your password is a word followed by "1980", use Join Attacks to combine Dictionary attack and Known Password/Part attack with the value set to "1980".
taskpane$semi$ node description for decr:
Decryptum Attack instantly decrypts MS Word and Excel files up to version 2003. It connects to the www.decryptum.com server to generate a free preview or to decrypt files.

You are required to purchase a Decryptum PIN to save the decrypted file. The partial preview of the file is free.
taskpane$semi$ node description for dict: Dictionary Attack checks thousands of words from dictionary files as possible passwords. Every word from the dictionary is tested in a variety of modifications according to the current attack settings.
taskpane$semi$ node description for empt: Select an attack from the list on the right and drag it to the main window. Set appropriate settings for each attack.
taskpane$semi$ node description for join:
Join Attacks group applies its attacks to different parts of the password. Set the whole password length first. Then add attacks to the Join Attacks group for each part of the password.

Example: For passwords like "green123", set the following Join Attacks group.
-------------------------
Join Attacks:
Password Length: from 8 to 8
-------------------------
  Dictionary Attack: English
  Password Length: from 5 to 5
  -----------------------
  Brute-force Attack: English
  Password Length: from 3 to 3
  Symbol Set: Numbers
  ----------------------
taskpane$semi$ node description for norm:
Pick up the Casing of your password. Then add an attack (Dictionary, Xieve, Brute-force, or Known Password/Part) to this Modifier.

For example, word "paSsWOrd" can be modified as:

Original: paSsWOrd
Normal: Password
Toggle: pASSWORD
Upper: PASSWORD
Lower: password
Reverse: PAsSwoRD
Mixed: PaSsWord.
taskpane$semi$ node description for rain:
Rainbow Tables Attack recovers hashed passwords from Windows, MD5, LANMAN, NTLM, SHA1 hashes. To calculate a password, it uses rainbow tables - precomputed tables for reversing cryptographic hash functions.

Rainbow tables are available for download at third-party websites, such as www.FreeRainbowTables.com. The attack supports .RT and .RTI2 tables.
taskpane$semi$ node description for reve:
Reverse your password:
"password" -> "drowssap".
Then add an attack (Dictionary, Xieve, Brute-force, or Known Password/Part) to this Modifier.
taskpane$semi$ node description for xiev: Xieve Attack checks only those combinations of characters that are common in English words. It dramatically boosts Brute-Force Attack speed by skipping nonsensical combinations of characters.

taskpane$semi$ veracrypt details:
Passware Kit scans a physical memory image file (acquired while the encrypted volume was mounted), extracts all the encryption keys, and decrypts the given volume. The image of the decrypted volume is saved. 

Please select the encrypted volume or partition, or its image (created with a tool, such as EnCase, DD, or WinHex) and the physical memory image file (created with Passware FireWire Memory Imager, or another tool, such as ManTech Memory DD or win32dd). Then select the location and name of the decrypted volume image. 

Personal Iterations Multiplier(PIM) is a parameter that controls the number of iterations used by the header key derivation function. If no PIM value is specified or PIM is 0, the default number of VeraCrypt iterations is used. The minimum PIM value for short passwords (19 characters and less) is 98 for system encryption and 485 for non-system encryption and files containers. For password with 20 characters and more, the minimum PIM value is 1.
